{{Infobox company | name = Cryptography Research, Inc. | logo = [[File:Cryptography Research logo.png|142px|Cryptography Research, Inc. Logo]] | | type = [[Private company|Private]] subsidiary | founded = {{start date and age|1995}} | location = [[San Francisco]], [[California]] | key_people = [[Paul Kocher]], President and Chief Scientist | products = Technology licensing, secure semiconductors | revenue = $10M-$100M | num_employees = 25-100 | homepage = [http://www.rambus.com/security www.rambus.com/security] | parent = [[Rambus]] }} '''Cryptography Research, Inc.''' is a [[San Francisco]] based cryptography company specializing in applied cryptographic engineering, including technologies for building tamper-resistant semiconductors. It was purchased on June 6, 2011 by [[Rambus]] for $342.5M.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/227797/rambus_buying_cryptography_research_for_3425_million.html | title=Rambus Buying Cryptography Research for $342.5 Million |date=2011-05-12 |accessdate=2012-06-16}}</ref> The company licenses patents for protecting cryptographic devices against [[power analysis]] attacks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frost.com/prod/servlet/market-insight-top.pag?docid=28127384|last=Ubhey |first=Anoop |title=Interview with Cryptography Research Inc |publisher= Frost.com |date=November 23, 2004}}</ref> The company's CryptoFirewall-brand [[ASIC]] cores are used in pay [[TV]] conditional access systems and anti-counterfeiting applications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devicelink.com/mddi/archive/07/10/020.html|first=Maria |last=Fontanezza |title=Technology Battles Device Cloning - MD&DI |date=October 2007|publisher=}}</ref> CRI also developed [[BD+]], a security component in the Blu-ray disc format, and played a role in the format war between [[HD DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/04/15/business/technology-plan-would-use-content-not-devices-to-fight-piracy.html|last=Markoff |first= John |title=Plan Would Use Content, Not Devices, to Fight Piracy |publisher= The New York Times |date=15 April 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.wired.com/27bstroke6/2008/02/how-crypto-won.html|first=Ryan |last=Singel |title=How Crypto Won the DVD War |publisher= Wired Magazine |date=February 28, 2008|work=WIRED}}</ref> The company's services group assists with security testing, disaster recovery, and training.
Cryptography Research protects its core operations from outside attack by maintaining a secured local network that is not connected to the [[Internet]] at all. Employees who need to work with sensitive data have two computers on their desks — one to access the secure network, and a separate computer to access the Internet.<ref>[http://news.cnet.com/8301-27080_3-20001391-245.html?tag=nl.e703 "How one company stays safe with two networks"], [[CNET News]], March 30, 2010.</ref>
In 2009, [[Frost & Sullivan]] awarded the company the World Smart Card Technology Leadership of the Year Award, noting that the company is "one of the highest-volume and highest-value technology licensors in the semiconductor industry" and that "more than 4 billion security chips are produced under its licenses every year".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frost.com/prod/servlet/press-release.pag?docid=179970706|title=Frost & Sullivan Commends Cryptography Research for Technology Leadership |date=September 15, 2009|publisher=frost.com}}</ref>
